Introduction

Gross Domestic Product is one of the most important economical measures which stands for the sum of the values of all the products and services delivered by companies, not necessarily originating from a country, but running their business in that country.

Therefore it is crucial and at the same time the most basic tool when comparing economies of various countries.

In this analysis I will take a look at the nominal GDP. It is probably the most common of GDP. It, as Iâ€™ve mentioned, does include only companies operating in a specific country and it summarizes the wealth of a nation as a whole, instead of showing how rich are its citizens, for which GDP per capita is used. The most important point is that it expresses the value of goods in nominal prices, in this case in millions of US dollars. In contrast, there is a version of GDP based of PPP (Purchasing Power Parity), which also takes into account prices and costs of living in a country.

Data source

In my analysis I will rely on data available on Wikipedia on that URL:

  • https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)

I am going to focus only on the data gathered by United Nations, as it is the most complete and, I believe, more common than the other sources.

The measurement of GDP is from the year 2021.

library(rvest)
page <- read_html("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)")
data <- html_node(page, ".wikitable")
data <- html_table(data, fill = TRUE, dec = ".")
WorldGDP <- data[2, 7]
data <- data[3:215,c(1,2,7)]

Preparing data

There is an issue that the comma signs are used to separate each 3 decimal places. I will also change the name of columns so it will be easier to refer to them.

deleteCommas <- function(x){as.numeric(gsub(",", "", x))}
data[,3] <- lapply(data[,3], deleteCommas)
WorldGDP <- deleteCommas(WorldGDP)
colnames(data)[2] <- "Region"
colnames(data)[3] <- "GDP"

Unfortunately data for Taiwan is NA, so I will drop this record.

data <- data[!is.na(data$GDP),]

Distribution of the GDP

Descriptive statistics

library(dplyr)
library(knitr)
library(moments)
data %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  summarize(Mean = mean(GDP), Median = median(GDP), "Standard Derivation" = sd(GDP), IQR = IQR(GDP), Skewness = skewness(GDP), Kurtosis = kurtosis(GDP)) %>%
  kable()
Region Mean Median Standard Derivation IQR Skewness Kurtosis
Africa 49575.33 15777.0 97687.0 39738.0 3.193286 12.471163
Americas 665623.76 16851.0 3438175.6 100641.2 6.419455 42.782780
Asia 734486.64 63910.5 2596811.1 377475.0 5.877525 38.409476
Europe 541276.57 149187.5 936630.5 501620.5 2.474820 8.684832
Oceania 119858.29 857.0 420414.5 5798.0 3.631022 14.455552

What can be seen is that Africa is the region with the lowest average GDP. However, if we take a look at the median it clearly suggest, which if fact seems logical, that Oceania has countries with smallest economies. This difference is, I think, mostly due to Australia, having one of the biggest economies in the world, being included there. Both the fact that in each case the mean is much higher than median and the skewness coefficient gives us the information that the distribution is strongly right-skewed.

library(ggplot2)
data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = GDP)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of GDP in the whole world", x = "GDP (mln USD)")

The histogram confirms that without any doubt. The vast majority of countries has the GDP much lower than the most rich ones.

Now letâ€™s have a look at the same plot with removed outliers. In this case let it be GDP lower than 1 billion USD.

library(ggplot2)
data %>%
  filter(GDP < 1000000) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = GDP)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of GDP in the whole world (no outliers)", x = "GDP (mln USD)")

Skewness here is still visible. Letâ€™s also look at it by regions.

data %>%
  filter(GDP < 1000000) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = GDP)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
  theme_light() +
  facet_wrap(~ Region) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of GDP in individual regions", x = "GDP (mln USD)")

The plots seem similar to one another and to the main plot, so there can be assumed that distribution does not diverge by a lot throughout the regions.

Next statistic to look at is the standard derivation. The biggest value is observable for the Americas. It is not unexpected as it is the region with either big economies such as the United States and really small ones, like various Caribbean nations. Nevertheless, it will give us more information if divided by the mean, making it a coefficient of variation.

data %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  summarize("Coefficient of variation" = sd(GDP)/mean(GDP)) %>%
  kable()
Region Coefficient of variation
Africa 1.970476
Americas 5.165344
Asia 3.535546
Europe 1.730410
Oceania 3.507596

It makes the matter even more transparent. The variation in the region of the Americas is almost three times as big as in Europe or Africa. The region of Asia and Oceania are also more divergent, the second being presumably thanks to the huge difference between Australia and islander nations.

The IQR highligths mostly two things already mentioned. Oceania has a lot of countries running tiny economies, whereas countries of Europe on average stay wealthy.

Because of the high skewness, the kurtosis does not bring in any valid information. By what was already discussed, we can already almost with certainty reject the assumption of normality of the distribution. Regardless of that letâ€™s perform some test to make sure.

library(nortest)
data %>%
  summarize("Shapio-Wilk Test" = shapiro.test(GDP)$p, "Kolmogorov Test" = ks.test(GDP, "pnorm", mean = mean(GDP), sd = sd(GDP))$p, "Pearson Test" = pearson.test(GDP)$p) %>% kable()
Shapio-Wilk Test Kolmogorov Test Pearson Test
0 0 0

Definitely, the normality of the distribution is out of question.

Lorenz curve

library(ineq)
lc <- Lc(data$GDP)
lc_dat <- data.frame(cbind(lc$p, lc$L))
ggplot(lc_dat, aes(x = X1, y = X2)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "navy") +
  labs(title = "GDP Distribution", subtitle = "Lorenz Curve",
       x = "Cumulative Proportion of Population",
       y = "Cumulative Proportion of Income") +
  theme_light()
